For instance, 
 Aristolochia albida Duch (0.2 RFC) has been prescribed for cancer treatment. While a species of 
 Aristolochia have been documented in a similar study (
 Ngulde et al., 2014), its toxic side effects have yet to be established. Generally, 
 Aristolochia and one of its chief components aristolochic acid have been known for its carcinogenic, and nephrotoxic effects for a very long time (
 Michael et al., 2009). Recently, several toxicological risks associated with a history of using herbal medicines containing aristolochic acid amongst cancer patients have been reported (
 Aydin et al., 2017; 
 Ban et al., 2018; 
 Chen et al., 2018; 
 Hoang et al., 2016; 
 Hung et al., 2016; 
 Kanaan et al., 2016; 
 Popovska-Jankovic et al., 2016; 
 Xiong et al., 2018; 
 Zhong et al., 2017). Despite the reported cases on the use of herbs containing aristolochic acid around the world, a similar effect associated with the use of 
 Aristolochia spp has yet to be reported in Nigeria.
